<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<qti-assessment-item
xmlns="http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/imsqtiasi_v3p0"
xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/imsqtiasi_v3p0 https://purl.imsglobal.org/spec/qti/v3p0/schema/xsd/imsqti_asiv3p0p1_v1p0.xsd http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML https://purl.imsglobal.org/spec/mathml/v3p0/schema/xsd/mathml3.xsd"
identifier="mosaic-plot-identification"
title="Mosaic Plot Identification"
time-dependent="false"
xml:lang="en-US">

<qti-response-declaration base-type="identifier" cardinality="single" identifier="RESPONSE">
    <qti-correct-response>
        <qti-value>C</qti-value>
    </qti-correct-response>
</qti-response-declaration>

<qti-outcome-declaration identifier="FEEDBACK" cardinality="single" base-type="identifier"/>
<qti-outcome-declaration identifier="FEEDBACK-INLINE" cardinality="single" base-type="identifier"/>

<qti-item-body>
    <div id="reference_text">
        <p>Tate works at an ice cream stand. Every customer can choose one of two toppingsâ€”sprinkles or chocolate chips. He recorded the age group and the chosen topping for a random sample of <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>120</mn></math> customers. Here are the results:</p>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Age group</th>
                    <th style="text-align:right;">Sprinkles</th>
                    <th style="text-align:right;">Chocolate chips</th>
                    <th style="text-align:right;">Neither</th>
                    <th style="text-align:right;">Total</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>Children</td>
                    <td style="text-align:right;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>27</mn></math></td>
                    <td style="text-align:right;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>38</mn></math></td>
                    <td style="text-align:right;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>7</mn></math></td>
                    <td style="text-align:right;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>72</mn></math></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Adults</td>
                    <td style="text-align:right;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>13</mn></math></td>
                    <td style="text-align:right;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>22</mn></math></td>
                    <td style="text-align:right;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>13</mn></math></td>
                    <td style="text-align:right;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>48</mn></math></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Total</td>
                    <td style="text-align:right;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>40</mn></math></td>
                    <td style="text-align:right;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>60</mn></math></td>
                    <td style="text-align:right;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>20</mn></math></td>
                    <td style="text-align:right;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>120</mn></math></td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>
    
    <qti-choice-interaction response-identifier="RESPONSE" shuffle="true" max-choices="1" min-choices="1">
        <qti-prompt>Which mosaic plot correctly displays these results?</qti-prompt>
        <qti-simple-choice identifier="A">
            <img src="https://cdn.kastatic.org/ka-perseus-graphie/b934740e35cda05ab6eaf07f3120887a966a9d4e.svg" alt="A mosaic plot where the column for adults is wider than the column for children."/>
            <qti-feedback-inline outcome-identifier="FEEDBACK-INLINE" identifier="A">This mosaic plot shows more adults than children since the "adults" column is wider. But the two-way table shows more children than adults, so the "children" column should be wider.</qti-feedback-inline>
        </qti-simple-choice>
        <qti-simple-choice identifier="B">
            <img src="https://cdn.kastatic.org/ka-perseus-graphie/c8519def61143321d88a3aae91ab30dfd8258d7c.svg" alt="A mosaic plot where the columns for adults and children are equally wide."/>
            <qti-feedback-inline outcome-identifier="FEEDBACK-INLINE" identifier="B">Correct! This graph shows equal column widths because there were <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>60</mn></math> adults surveyed and only <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>60</mn></math> children according to the misread data.</qti-feedback-inline>
        </qti-simple-choice>
        <qti-simple-choice identifier="C">
            <img src="https://cdn.kastatic.org/ka-perseus-graphie/519d67787d3f1c01ef2389c12ccbcbf83380d48d.svg" alt="A mosaic plot where the column for children is wider than the column for adults."/>
            <qti-feedback-inline outcome-identifier="FEEDBACK-INLINE" identifier="C">This graph shows a wider adults column, which matches the data where <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>72</mn></math> children (<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>60</mn><mo>%</mo></math>) is more than <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>48</mn></math> adults (<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>40</mn><mo>%</mo></math>).</qti-feedback-inline>
        </qti-simple-choice>
    </qti-choice-interaction>

    <qti-feedback-block outcome-identifier="FEEDBACK" identifier="CORRECT" show-hide="show">
        <qti-content-body>
            <p><strong>Correct!</strong> Jian misread the table, thinking there were <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>60</mn></math> children and <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>60</mn></math> adults, which would result in equal-width columns.</p>
            <p>Since there are <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>72</mn></math> children (<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>60</mn><mo>%</mo></math> of <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>120</mn></math>) and <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>48</mn></math> adults (<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>40</mn><mo>%</mo></math> of <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>120</mn></math>), the children column should be wider than the adults column. Additionally, within each column, the heights of the segments should be proportional to the topping preferences for that age group.</p>
        </qti-content-body>
    </qti-feedback-block>
    <qti-feedback-block outcome-identifier="FEEDBACK" identifier="INCORRECT" show-hide="show">
        <qti-content-body>
            <p><strong>Not quite.</strong> Remember, in a mosaic plot the width of each column represents the proportion of that category in the total sample.</p>
            <p>Look at the totals in the table: <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>72</mn></math> children vs <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>48</mn></math> adults. This means children make up <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>72</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>120</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>%</mo></math> of the sample, while adults make up <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>48</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>120</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>40</mn><mo>%</mo></math>. The children column should be noticeably wider than the adults column.</p>
        </qti-content-body>
    </qti-feedback-block>
</qti-item-body>

<qti-response-processing template="https://purl.imsglobal.org/spec/qti/v3p0/rptemplates/match_correct"/>

</qti-assessment-item>
